Studio favorites ✨
Ron Gorchov, Chicago, USA, 1930-2020

We are in love with Gorchov’s ability to harmonize shape and colors in his compositions. His paintings created a sense of depth and dimensionality that translates in a captivating visual experience 🤍 

Ron Gorchov was an American artist known for his distinctive and innovative "saddle" paintings, which featured canvas stretched over curved wooden frames, creating a three-dimensional effect. His work often explored the relationship between shape and color, and he was associated with the post-minimalist and a-5bstract expressionist movements. Gorchov's art career spanned several decades, and his contributions to the art world have left a lasting impact. His works are part of the permanent collections of The Met, Moma,Whitney and Guggenheim among many others.

Casa La Cupola, Costa Paradiso, Sardinia, Italy, 1969
Architect Dante Bini @binishells 

La Cupola house was designed for the famous Italian director Michelangelo Antonioni and his then lover, actress Monica Vitti, by Italian architect Dante Bini. 
In the ‘60s Bini invented a unique construction technique where reinforced concrete thin-shell structures are lifted and shaped by air pressure. He built 1,600 of his Binishells in 23 countries.
Unfortunately by the time the house was ready in 1972, Antonioni and Vitti love story was already at the end and they never lived in the house together.

Carlo Mollino’s apartment, Turin, Italy, built between 1960 and 1968 
Architect Carlo Mollino

The eclectic artist lived all his life in the family home in Rivoli, but on the death of his father, he inherited a small apartment in the center of Turin, in a small villa of the late nineteenth century. Here, between 1960 and 1968 he spent time designing every detail, inspired by the tomb that the Egyptian architect Kha, in the service of the pharaoh Amenhotep III, had built in the fourteenth century BC for himself and his wife Merit. It is a secret refuge, unknown even to his closest friends like Carol Rama who lived on the same street, populated by artifacts of all kinds. The rooms are full of a mix'n match that resembles more a bric-à-brac shop than a house. So it's no coincidence that Mollino hasn't spent a single night here (it's said that he hasn't even opened the windows). [Text Kettj Talon]

Safari Sofa, Poltronova, Italy, 1968
Designer Archizoom Associati

The Safari Sofa is an iconic and impactful piece of design due to its visionary approach to furniture. Created in the late 1960s by the Italian design collective "Archizoom," it challenged conventional notions of seating by embracing modularity and flexibility. The sofa's design allowed users to arrange and reconfigure it in various ways, promoting individuality and adaptability in living spaces. 

Its minimalist, futuristic aesthetic and innovative use of materials also marked a departure from traditional "one-size-fits-all" furniture design, offering  a critique of the disposable tendencies of consumerism. 

The choice of the leopard pattern was a cultured reference to the work Bedroom ensemble (1963) by Claes Oldenburg, master of English Pop Art, and his subsequent Leopard chair, but also to a Kitsch taste adopted by the group in polemic with the need to make form follow function.

The Safari Sofa remains a timeless symbol of avant-garde design and continues to influence contemporary furniture concepts.

John Baldessari, 1931-2020

John Baldessari was known for deconstructing and recontextualizing existing images and art. He would take familiar imagery and alter it, sometimes obscuring or manipulating certain elements to provoke new interpretations. Highly influenced by Pop Art, he worked with commercial imagery and bold color deliberately, and was considered an iconoclast for challenging established artistic norms and traditions. 

His conceptual and irreverent approach cemented him as a pivotal figure in the development and popularization of conceptual art in the 1960s and 1970s, and led him to influence and inspire emerging artists as an educator at California Institute of the Arts.

Prentice Women’s Hospital, Chicago, Illinois, 1975
Architect Bertrand Goldberg

The Prentice Women's Hospital stood as a brutalist landmark and a representati on of Chicago's commitment to architectural innovation. The building's shell structure and unique design that cantilevered out from a central core minimized interior support columns, allowing for flexibility in layout and the ability to offer a more unified patient care model. The hospital also stood out from the rectilinear, modernist structures that were typical of the time, with its quatrefoil concrete design. Sadly, demands for modern medical infrastructure were met by demolishing the building in 2013, although this remains a subject of architectural and preservation debates.

Les Choux de Créteil, Créteil, France, 1969-1974
Architect Gérard Grandval
📷 @massmoderndesign 

Diving into the rich history of Les Choux de Créteil, these iconic Brutalist buildings are not just structures, but a testament to architectural innovation. Designed by Gérard Grandval in the late 1960s, ‘Les Choux’ (The Cabbages) is a cluster of unique residential towers in Créteil, France. The striking choice of raw concrete and geometric forms reflects the Brutalist movement’s ethos – an unapologetic celebration of functionality and simplicity.

Originally conceived as a response to the growing demand for affordable housing, Les Choux de Créteil has since become a symbol of urban resilience and community. Each tower, resembling a giant cabbage with its segmented structure, stands as a reminder of an era when architects experimented with unconventional designs to address societal needs.

Despite initial controversies, these buildings have endured and evolved, gaining appreciation for their historical significance and architectural prowess. Today, wandering through the corridors of Les Choux offers a journey through time, connecting us to the visionaries who dared to challenge the norms. An architectural masterpiece that tells a story of innovation, purpose, and the enduring legacy of Brutalism

The National Autonomous University of Mexico (UNAM) has several libraries, each with its own unique architecture. One notable example is the Central Library, or “Biblioteca Central” in Spanish. Designed by architect Juan O’Gorman, it is an iconic structure known for its mosaic murals that depict the history of Mexico. The library consists of two towers, each representing different historical periods – one for the pre-Hispanic era and another for the post-Conquest period. The use of bold colors and intricate details in the murals makes the UNAM Central Library a distinctive architectural landmark.

Cy Twombly, 1928 - 2011

Edwin Parker “Cy” Twombly Jr. was an American painter, sculptor and photographer. His work seamlessly fused elements of abstract expressionism with conceptual art, challenging traditional artistic boundaries. Twombly’s use of symbolism, raw emotion, and spontaneous creativity set him apart, creating a deeply personal and enigmatic visual language.

His large-scale canvases often conveyed a sense of immediacy and dynamism, inviting viewers to interpret and engage with the complexity of his layered compositions.

Notre-Dame-du-Haut, Ronchamp, France, 1955
Architect Le Corbusier 
📷 Unknown, via @le_cime 

The Notre-Dame du Haut is a modernist Catholic chapel located in Ronchamp, France. Designed by architect Le Corbusier, it is known for its innovative architecture, featuring curved walls and a unique roof design. 

Notre-Dame du Haut holds significance in architectural history as a prime example of 20th-century modernist and brutalist architecture. Le Corbusier’s design emphasizes simplicity, raw materials, and a departure from traditional styles. The use of reinforced concrete, sculptural forms, and the incorporation of light through strategically placed openings are characteristic of brutalist principles.

Despite being associated with brutalism, Notre-Dame du Haut stands out as a poetic and contemplative space, showcasing the versatility of the architectural style beyond its often stern and utilitarian reputation. The chapel’s influence extends beyond its religious purpose, leaving a lasting impact on the discourse of modern architecture.
